    en: "Clarkson runs an unusual permit-and-inspection structure compared with its neighbors: a separate plumbing permit, a clear per-fixture fee, and a sharp double-fee penalty for skipping the permit.\n\nSeparate plumbing permit. Clarkson requires a plumbing permit on a separate form from the general building permit. The plumbing permit triggers its own inspection and its own fee.\n\nFee structure. The published residential fee schedule: $65 flat plus $2 per fixture. Commercial work: $100 flat plus $10 per fixture. A '$65 + $2/fixture' permit for a bathroom with 5 fixtures (sink, toilet, tub, shower, drain) costs $75. A kitchen with 2 fixtures (sink, dishwasher) costs $69. The schedule dates from 2018 and remains the active fee list. Confirming the current amount with the Building Department avoids surprises if the schedule has been revised.\n\nDouble fee for unpermitted work. Starting plumbing work before pulling the permit doubles the fee. On a 5-fixture job, that is $75 vs $150 — meaningful on a small job, and larger on a big one. Pulling the permit first is always the cheaper path.\n\nSewer hookup. A new sewer hookup is a separate process with separate costs: $125 to the town plus a $250 Monroe County Pure Waters fee. The county fee covers the connection at the public main.\n\nNo plumber licensing chapter. Clarkson does not run its own plumber licensing. Insurance verification replaces the license process. A plumber working in Clarkson has to show current general liability insurance and workers' compensation coverage at permit application. A qualifying sole proprietor can show a CE-200 waiver in place of workers' comp.\n\nReciprocity. Whether Clarkson honors a City of Rochester Examining Board of Plumbers certificate as a basis for working in the town is not published. Calling the Building Department confirms for a specific plumber.\n\nHomeowner self-work. Whether a homeowner can pull the plumbing permit in their own name and do the work is not fully published on the town's fee schedule. The default New York rule allows it with a permit and inspection, but Clarkson's Building Department has the final word for town-specific practice.\n\nInspection flow. A Clarkson town inspector performs the plumbing inspection; the town does not use third-party agencies for plumbing. Inspections typically occur at rough-in (before walls are closed up) and at final.\n\nGas piping. Gas line work from the meter to the appliance is plumbing work. Clarkson requires the same plumber-and-permit cycle for gas piping.\n\nBrockport village boundary. The Village of Brockport sits inside Clarkson (and Sweden). Addresses inside Brockport village limits go through the village Building Department, not Clarkson. The tax assessor confirms which office handles a specific address.\n\nFailed inspection or unpermitted work. The Town Code Enforcement Officer can require corrections, tear-out, or a full redo when work was done without a permit or does not meet code. Unpermitted plumbing work can block a future certificate of occupancy check and can surface at resale.\n\nState-level rules. Wage theft protections (Labor Law 191 and 193), the Scaffold Law (LL 240 and 241(6)), mechanic's liens for unpaid work (Lien Law 3 and 10), and General Business Law 349 for deceptive contractors apply in Clarkson as they do statewide. The plumbing-residential-ny entry covers those layers."
